## Step 2 — the task/gate loop

For each task (in `depends_on` order), **do the work inline by default**:

1. **design-before-code** — a short DRY/SOLID pass. Reject a design that re-introduces a
   copy. For a non-trivial task, write it to `artifacts/<task-slug>/<subject>-design-<YYYY-MM-DD>.md`
   (descriptive slug + descriptive, dated filename — never `artifacts/t5/design-3.md`; see Naming
   discipline below).
2. **implement** — first read the task's **`dispatch`** field in `TASKS.yaml` (`inline` default /
   `worker` / `fresh_session`):
   - **`fresh_session`** — a **self-modifying** task: it edits files the running session loads and
     depends on (`.claude/agents/**`, `.claude/skills/**`, hooks, `settings.json`). You **cannot** do
     this inline OR via a worker/`Agent` dispatch — every in-session subagent inherits *this* session
     and its permissions, so editing what the session loaded causes hook conflicts + partial state. See
     the **Self-modifying tasks** box in Step 3 for the handoff.
   - **`worker` / heavier machinery** — inline in one followable diff by default; reach for a worker
     ONLY when the task needs it (see "Workflow vs inline" in Step 3): (b) large + self-contained or
     (c) needs an independent/cold perspective → **one `Agent` dispatch** of the **worker** profile
     (`{{team}}-worker`, own worktree; escalate hard 2+-module questions to **advisor**
     `{{team}}-advisor`) — a single `Agent`, NOT a Workflow. (a) genuine N-way parallel fan-out →
     the **Workflow tool** (Step 3), never a hand-rolled loop of single dispatches. Otherwise stay inline.
   **When you DO dispatch** (Agent or Workflow), hand the subagent a **scoped brief** — the task + the
   exact artifacts to read — not "go read the KB". The worker/advisor keep their own **native persistent
   memory** across dispatches (`.claude/agent-memory/{{team}}-worker|advisor/`), so you do NOT harvest
   learnings back — they self-curate. **Provider-outage fallback:** if a dispatch fails because the agent's model tier is globally
   unavailable, retry one tier down (e.g. fable → opus) rather than failing the task — a transient
   provider outage should not stall the loop.
   **Worktree boundary — never edit a live worker's tree.** While a dispatched worker is active, do
   **not** edit, commit, or push inside its worktree: from inside a worktree your edits are
   indistinguishable from a hostile third party, so the worker resets them and escalates (a real run
   had a worker file a false "rogue agent" issue over exactly this). Route review findings on a
   worker's branch **back to the worker** as a follow-up dispatch; if you must take over, tell it to
   **stand down and wait for its confirmation** before touching the tree.
3. **gate** — run the task's `gate_set` (defined in `TASKS.yaml.gates`, scaled to
   `blast_radius`). **Never advance on red** — fix in place and re-gate. Any gate SCRIPT you
   author (parity check, deletion-safety cert) lives at `.claude/team-forge/{{team}}/gates/` with a
   descriptive name (`parity-check.py`) — tracked, not an ad-hoc playground script.
4. **commit** on `{{integration_branch}}`. The commit log is the story — write the message
   in the task's human-readable NAME, never its ID (`T5`). The reader has no ID decoder.
5. **update the ledger — per-task AND rollup fields** — set the task `status: done` +
   `gate_status` + `commit`, append a `task_completed` event, AND refresh the summary/rollup
   fields the dashboard panels read (these are separate from the per-task record and are the ones
   most often left stale): `current_task` ← next eligible task; `integration_branch.pr_url` when a
   PR opens; `budget` /
   `token_spend_cumulative_k`. (`integration_branch.head_sha` you do NOT hand-maintain — the
   renderer derives it live from git.) Keep `status.json` a THIN index. (A dispatched worker/advisor
   records its own cross-dispatch learnings in its native agent memory — nothing for you to harvest.)
   Then **refresh the dashboard** (see **Observability**) and glance at the panels — a summary panel
   that didn't move means an un-updated rollup field, not a render bug.
6. **loop** to the next task whose `depends_on` are all `done`.

## Step 3 — fan-out (bounded bursts, via the Workflow tool)

**Workflow vs inline — pick the lightest mechanism that fits:**

| Situation | Mechanism |
|---|---|
| One task, one diff — the normal case | **Inline.** You do design→implement→gate yourself; no subagent, no Workflow. |
| ONE piece that's large + self-contained, or needs an independent/cold perspective | **One `Agent` dispatch** (a worker or advisor). Still not a Workflow. |
| Real N-way parallelism, or a fan-out→synthesize→adversarial-verify over multiple items | **Workflow tool** (a bounded burst). Appears in `/workflows`. |
| A **`fresh_session`** task — edits `.claude/agents/**`, `.claude/skills/**`, hooks, or `settings.json` | **Neither.** No subagent can do it (they inherit this session). **Hand off to a fresh session** — see box below. |

**Self-modifying tasks (`dispatch: fresh_session`) — you hand off, you don't dispatch.** A task that
edits the agent/skill/hook/settings files *this* session has loaded cannot be done by any in-session
agent — inline or worker/`Agent`, they all inherit this session's loaded config + permissions, so the
edit races the very files in play. For such a task you:
1. **Prepare** — write the scoped brief to `artifacts/<task-slug>/` and set up the target branch/worktree.
2. **Record** — mark the task `blocked_on: fresh_session_handoff` in `status.json` (a legitimate stop,
   like the plan-gate — you physically cannot self-serve it), log the event.
3. **Keep moving if you can** — if other tasks have satisfied `depends_on`, continue the loop on them;
   only pause the whole run if *everything* is blocked on this handoff.
4. **Hand off** — tell the user exactly what to launch: a fresh Claude session in a split window with
   full permissions, pointed at the brief + branch. Resume the task (gate → commit → ledger) once it lands.

Invoking this launcher **is** your authorization to call the Workflow tool at the burst points below
— you don't need to re-ask the user. But trigger it **only** when there's real parallelism to exploit:
a single item or a trivial task stays inline (a pipeline of one is pure overhead). When you do burst,
call the **Workflow tool** for a bounded run that instantiates the worker/verifier profile N-way, then
collapse back to this loop:
- **parallel build** — N independent tasks/items at once (e.g. a per-module migration).
- **verification fan-out** — M facet-maps + K adversarial verdicts → synthesize a
  certification doc under `artifacts/<task-slug>/`.

Do NOT hand-roll a sequential loop of single dispatches in place of a genuine burst — you lose the
concurrency and the run won't show in `/workflows`. agent-teams is **not** used: fan-out is the
Workflow tool; the steady state is this lead loop.

**Adversarial critique is REQUIRED, not optional, on medium/high `blast_radius` tasks.** The
fan-out → synthesize → **adversarial-critique** → revise loop is what catches load-bearing errors
(silent signal-flips, double-applies, silent-success-on-failed-write) — cosmetics survive without it,
real bugs don't. For any non-trivial change, run at least one critic pass whose explicit job is to
REFUTE the result before you propagate; record its verdict in the certification doc. A green gate set
without a critic pass is not "verified."

## Step 4 — re-plan (design is a living artifact — W7)

When a gate result or an implementation discovery invalidates the plan:
1. Write a new dated plan `team-plans/<slug>-plan-<YYYY-MM-DD>.md` with a one-line **why**
   (same-day re-cut → append `-v2`; the slug names the plan's focus, never generic).
2. Re-cut **only the not-yet-done** tasks + their gates in `TASKS.yaml`; preserve gated/committed work.
3. Update `status.json`: `current_plan` ← new path, append the old to `plan_history`, log a `replanned` event.
4. Review the re-cut (design-before-code, at the plan level) before resuming.

A refactor that never pivots probably wasn't understood — expect to re-plan.

## Memory authority (single-writer)

You own `status.json` (kept thin) + `runtime/` + `artifacts/` + `team-plans/`. A dispatched worker
writes only its worktree; it also self-curates its **own** native persistent memory
(`.claude/agent-memory/{{team}}-worker|advisor/`, auto-managed by Claude Code) — that is the agent's,
not yours. `gen_dashboard.py` renders `dashboard.html` mechanically.

## Naming discipline (IDs stay internal)

Task IDs (`T5`, `m1`) are **internal-ledger-only** — they live in `TASKS.yaml` + `status.json`
and nowhere else. Every outward surface uses the task's human-readable NAME:

- **commit messages, PR titles** — name the work, not the ID.
- **code comments** — never write `# honour T5 write-only-first`; describe the behaviour.
- **artifact filenames** — content-descriptive **+ dated**: `<subject>-<artifact-kind>-<YYYY-MM-DD>.md`
  (`migration-plan-2026-07-02.md`), never a generic/undated `design-3.md`. Successive docs stay
  distinguishable. **Fixed-name contracts are exempt** (`design.yaml`, `status.json`, `TASKS.yaml`,
  `manifest.json`, `dashboard.html`) — resolved by fixed name.
- **artifact directories** — descriptive slug (`artifacts/post-process-runner/`), never `artifacts/t5/`.

If an ID must appear on a durable surface for cross-reference, include a one-line glossary so the
artifact is self-decoding.

